title: Hutch 2.2 alarm was tripped for unknown reasons
text:
Giacomo called around 19:00 to ask me to help him search Hutch 2.2 so he could enable class four laser mode for some work he needed to do. He told me he would contact the Duty Tech tomorrow to have the search dropped and the hutch opened. Around 22:50 our custodian alerted me to the fact that the Hutch 2.2 alarm was sounding. I went to the HPS panel and confirmed the following:

The hutch Stoppers were in.

The search for the hutch had dropped. 

The LSS system had not tripped and was still in class four mode.

None of the E-stops had been tripped.

Both doors were still magnetically locked.

No people were involved in the alarm going off.

The only fault I could confirm was the the alarm.

I contacted Alyssa, Kayla and Giacomo and alerted them of the situation. Using the Hutch online key I reset the hutch to stop the alarm. I have attached pictures of the HPS and LSS panels as they were after unlocking the doors but before resetting the hutch.

text: A. Johnson looked at the station and says that it has likely been misbehaving since 3/15 when the beam volts, focus, phase, etc. dropped out and did not recover properly (see plots). This was during the PAMM, and I'm not aware of any work that was done on it then, but it looks like the LI11 micro was rebooted around the same time. If 11-5 has been misbehaving since the PAMM, it may have escaped our notice due to the problems we were having with 11-1 as well. He says that IPL-ing the LI11 micro may be a good next step in troubleshooting, and will update the CATER (155839).

Shift Summary: Saturday Owl Shift
text: SUMMARY: User beam for 5.4hrs of this 12 hour shift. Insertion device gap motion failure. INJECTOR: 325mV Q, no tuning required for user beam autofills. Standby otherwise. SPEAR: Lost all beam at 0430 due to a suspected power dip. Recovered everything except unable to withdraw BL-15 ID gap to 20mm which is required for injection by the IVUN MPS interlock. BL-15 ID gap was at 9.6mm and unable to pull out, thus preventing injection. System Mgr. was contacted and, along with technical support, tried everything possible remotely to no avail. System Mgr, came onsite. Set SPEAR ring access at 0830. Determined the problem was mechanical and a non-engaging clutch. MSG came onsite and fixed the problem. Re-delivered user beam at 1111. 6.7 hrs downtime. This opportunity was taken to have the SPEAR1 server rebooted to activate new patches. 500mA stored and 5-minute topoff injections have resumed at the end of the shift.
